INSERT INTO ARTICLE VALUES(1,0,1,'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\u000d\u000a<xml>\u000d\u000a    <practicenote>\u000d\u000a        <metadata>\u000d\u000a            <revhistory>\u000d\u000a                <revision>\u000d\u000a                    <revtitle>Finance Bill 2012</revtitle>\u000d\u000a                    <date>7 July 2012</date>\u000d\u000a                    <author>PLC Private Client</author>\u000d\u000a                    <revdescription>\u000d\u000a                        <section1 id="a724509">\u000d\u000a                            <para>We have updated this practice note to reflect the draft clauses included in the\u000d\u000a                                Finance Bill 2012 amd the announcement in the Budget on 21 March 2012 of two\u000d\u000a                                consultations to be published in July 2012. We have also included an additional\u000d\u000a                                section on the reduction in the rate of IHT for gifts of 10% or more of the net\u000d\u000a                                estate to charity.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </section1>\u000d\u000a                    </revdescription>\u000d\u000a                </revision>\u000d\u000a                <revision>\u000d\u000a                    <revtitle>Budget 2009: APR and woodlands relief extended to property within the EEA</revtitle>\u000d\u000a                    <date>23-Apr-2009</date>\u000d\u000a                    <author>PLC Private Client</author>\u000d\u000a                    <revdescription>\u000d\u000a                        <section1 id="a410603">\u000d\u000a                            <para>This practice note has been amended to reflect the fact that on 22 April 2009, the\u000d\u000a                                Chancellor announced that APR and woodlands relief will be extended to cover\u000d\u000a                                property within the European Economic Area (EEA), following the European\u000d\u000a                                Commission''s formal request to the UK to change the legislation.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </section1>\u000d\u000a                    </revdescription>\u000d\u000a                </revision>\u000d\u000a            </revhistory>\u000d\u000a        </metadata>\u000d\u000a        <fulltext>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a882719">\u000d\u000a                <title>Introduction to inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Inheritance tax (IHT) is primarily a charge on an individual''s\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">estate</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    on death. However, it can also arise on certain lifetime gifts, for example:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to certain trusts (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts:\u000d\u000a                            relevant property trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to companies (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts involving close companies (see\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Gifts made by close companies</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            and<emphasis role="italic">Alteration of share capital</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Ongoing IHT charges can also arise on trust property under the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">relevant property regime</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property regime</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In addition, IHT may be payable on outright gifts made within seven years of an individual''s\u000d\u000a                    death. This is mainly to catch those who try to avoid an IHT charge by giving away their estate\u000d\u000a                    shortly before they die. These are called\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (PETs) (see<emphasis role="italic">Potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The word "gift" is not used in the IHT legislation, although it is used in this note for ease.\u000d\u000a                    The legislation actually uses defined terms such as "disposition", "transfer of value" and\u000d\u000a                    "chargeable transfer", which cover a wide range of circumstances not always immediately\u000d\u000a                    recognised as being "gifts". The purpose is to cover lifetime transactions that result in a loss\u000d\u000a                    to the donor''s estate (and an increase in the donee''s estate), unless the transaction is for\u000d\u000a                    genuine commercial reasons and there is no gratuitous intent.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The legislation does not only cover gifts of cash or specific assets. It also covers, for\u000d\u000a                    example, sales of assets (for less than their full market value) to certain family members,\u000d\u000a                    fixed-term interest free loans and the rent-free use of property. There are also specific types\u000d\u000a                    of "excluded property" which fall outside the scope of the IHT legislation.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Every individual has a nil rate band in which IHT is charged at 0% (see<emphasis\u000d\u000a                        role="italic">The nil rate band</emphasis>). In addition to this, there are allowances,\u000d\u000a                    exemptions and reliefs which reduce the amount of IHT payable, if certain conditions are met.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The IHT legislation is contained in the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">Inheritance Tax Act 1984</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (IHTA 1984).\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">HM Revenue &amp; Customs</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (HMRC) have published detailed guidance on this topic, which is contained in\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Inheritance Tax Manual</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (IHT manual).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a609034">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Future review?</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>On 3 March 2011, the Office of Tax Simplification (OTS) published a final report on its\u000d\u000a                        tax reliefs review, which was commissioned by the Coalition government in November 2010. In\u000d\u000a                        its report, the OTS recommended that IHT reliefs be reviewed in the context of a separate\u000d\u000a                        review of IHT as a whole and that any review of IHT must include a review of the taxation of\u000d\u000a                        trusts (see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, Final report on tax reliefs review: private\u000d\u000a                            client exemptions and reliefs: Reliefs to be reviewed separately</emphasis>). For the\u000d\u000a                        latest information on the OTS review of tax reliefs and the government''s response to the\u000d\u000a                        review, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2011-12: Office of\u000d\u000a                            Tax Simplification reviews</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>HMRC published a The government announced, in its Budget on 21 March 2012, that it will p\u000d\u000a                        ublish a consultation document in July 2012 on its plans to simplify the way IHT is\u000d\u000a                        calculated for ten yearly charges and exit charges in<emphasis role="italic">relevant\u000d\u000a                            property trusts</emphasis>. The month set for publication is now known to be July 2012.\u000d\u000a                        It will publish a further consultation on these reforms in the spring of 2013. To follow the\u000d\u000a                        outcome of the consultation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client legislation tracker\u000d\u000a                            2012-13: IHT: simplifying calculations for relevant property trusts</emphasis>. For more\u000d\u000a                        information on how relevant property trusts are currently taxed, see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            Relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a724773">\u000d\u000a                <title>Territorial scope of inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The extent to which an individual is charged to IHT depends on their\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">domicile</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    status:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An individual who is domiciled in the UK is subject to IHT on their worldwide\u000d\u000a                            estate.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An individual who is not domiciled in the UK is subject to IHT only on their UK\u000d\u000a                            estate.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>"Domicile" is a complex concept which is based on a long line of cases in the field of\u000d\u000a                    international law. It has been incorporated into the IHT legislation as a means of reducing\u000d\u000a                    exposure to IHT for those who have only a temporary link with the UK.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In this context, domicile has a specific legal meaning, beyond the simple dictionary\u000d\u000a                    definition of "place of residence". An individual can be resident in the UK for many years and\u000d\u000a                    yet be domiciled elsewhere. In certain (more unusual) circumstances, an individual can also be\u000d\u000a                    domiciled in the UK without having set foot here. For further information on domicile, see\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Domicile</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In addition, Parliament decided that certain individuals should be subject to IHT on their\u000d\u000a                    worldwide estate, even though they are not domiciled in the UK under the general law. The\u000d\u000a                    rationale for this is that they have lived in the UK for a long time and should therefore\u000d\u000a                    contribute more tax. The following individuals are "deemed domiciled" in the UK for IHT\u000d\u000a                    purposes:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Individuals who have lived in the UK for at least 17 out of the previous 20 tax years.\u000d\u000a                            These individuals will be "deemed domiciled" in the UK from the start of their 17th tax\u000d\u000a                            year of residence.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>UK domiciled individuals who leave the UK and acquire a new domicile abroad. These\u000d\u000a                            individuals will be "deemed domiciled" for three years following the date they acquired\u000d\u000a                            their new domicile.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 267 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Examples of how these rules work can be found in<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Domicile: Deemed domicile</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a244616">\u000d\u000a                <title>The charge to tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Broadly, IHT is charged as follows:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="bold">On death</emphasis>, in relation to a deceased person''s estate.\u000d\u000a                            This includes:\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>gifts made in the seven years prior to death (see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    Potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>); and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="bold">On chargeable lifetime gifts</emphasis>. For example:\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts by close companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>An\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">alteration of share capital</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    by close companies.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">On trust property under the relevant property regime</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property\u000d\u000a                            trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a460375">\u000d\u000a                <title>The rate of tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>IHT is charged at the following rates:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>On the\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">nil rate band</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            amount, the rate of tax is 0% (that is, there is no IHT to pay).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>On the balance, the rate of tax is:</para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>20% for chargeable lifetime gifts (see<emphasis role="italic">The charge to\u000d\u000a                                    tax</emphasis>); and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>40% on estates on death (or 36% where 10% or more of the net estate is given\u000d\u000a                                    to charity, see<emphasis role="italic">10% reduction in rate of inheritance tax\u000d\u000a                                        for gifts to charity</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 7 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Relevant property trusts have their own charging regime (see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                    Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For more information on IHT rates and allowances, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Tax data for individuals and trustees</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Paragraph 207 and Schedule 32 of the Finance Bill 2012 provide for the application of a\u000d\u000a                    reduced rate of IHT to the estates of deceased individuals who leave 10% or more of their net\u000d\u000a                    estate to charity. For further information on this measure, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice\u000d\u000a                        note, Inheritance tax: leaving 10% of an estate to charity</emphasis>. To follow the\u000d\u000a                    progress of the measure towards implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax\u000d\u000a                        legislation tracker 2011-12: IHT: reduced rate for charitable testators</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a938367">\u000d\u000a                <title>The nil rate band</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The nil rate band is so called, because it is the amount which is chargeable to IHT at 0%.\u000d\u000a                    Each individual currently has a maximum nil rate band amount of \u00a3325,000 . It was announced in\u000d\u000a                    the 2009 Budget that the nil rate band amount would be frozen at \u00a3325,000 until 5 February 2015.\u000d\u000a                    , which is frozen until 5 April 2015 (see<emphasis role="italic">June 2010 Budget: key private\u000d\u000a                        client tax announcements: IHT nil rate band to remain frozen at \u00a3325,000 until 5 April\u000d\u000a                        2015</emphasis>) . The Secretary of State for Health, Jeremy Hunt, announced on 11 February\u000d\u000a                    2013 that the nil rate band would be frozen at this level for a further three years from 2015-16\u000d\u000a                    to meet part of the costs of changes to the funding of social care.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>This is the maximum amount, because the nil rate band can be used up in lifetime by:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Chargeable lifetime gifts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">PETs</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            made within the seven years before death.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>In the 2011 Budget, the government announced that from 2015-16, the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">consumer prices index</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (CPI) would be used as the "default indexation assumption" for the nil rate band, instead of the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">retail prices index</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (RPI). Draft legislation was published on 6 December 2011 for inclusion in the Finance Bill\u000d\u000a                    2012. The draft legislation provides for automatic indexation of the nil rate band each year,\u000d\u000a                    using the CPI over the year to the previous September, although this may be overridden for a tax\u000d\u000a                    year if Parliament sets a different figure. To follow the progress of this measure towards\u000d\u000a                    implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2011-12: IHT:\u000d\u000a                        CPI indexation of nil rate band</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For further information about the nil rate band, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Inheritance tax transferable nil rate band: overview</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For historic nil rate band amounts, see<emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Inheritance Tax\u000d\u000a                    thresholds</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For more information on IHT rates and allowances, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Tax data for individuals and trustees</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a654920">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Surviving spouse or civil partner can inherit unused portion of nil rate band</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>As a result of a change introduced by the<emphasis role="italic">Finance Act\u000d\u000a                        2008</emphasis>, a surviving spouse or\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">civil partner</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (who dies on or after 9 October 2007) can now effectively "inherit" the unused percentage of\u000d\u000a                        their deceased spouse or partner''s nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Jermaine dies in September 2007 and, on death, has assets of \u00a3500,000. His\u000d\u000a                        nil rate band of \u00a3300,000 is fully intact. He leaves a \u00a375,000 legacy to his daughter Dot,\u000d\u000a                        and the remainder of his estate to his wife Marnie.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>No IHT is payable on the assets passing to Marnie, because of the spouse exemption\u000d\u000a                                (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts to a spouse or civil partner</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>No IHT is payable on the legacy to Dot because it falls within Jermaine''s nil rate\u000d\u000a                                band.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Jermaine has essentially "wasted" 75% of his nil rate band.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>On Marnie''s death in September 2008, she has assets of \u00a3600,000 in her estate. Her nil\u000d\u000a                        rate band of \u00a3312,000 is fully intact. She leaves everything to Dot.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Marnie had died before 9 October 2007, the IHT payable on her estate would have\u000d\u000a                                been \u00a3115,200 (\u00a3600,000 - \u00a3312,000 x 40%).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Since she died after that date, the Finance Act 2008 will apply. Because Jermaine\u000d\u000a                                did not use 75% of his nil rate band, Marnie''s executors can claim an additional 75%\u000d\u000a                                of the nil rate band amount in force at the date of her death. Her "uplifted" nil\u000d\u000a                                rate band is therefore \u00a3546,000 (\u00a3312,000 + \u00a3234,000). The IHT payable on her death\u000d\u000a                                is therefore \u00a321,600 (\u00a3600,000 - \u00a3546,000 x 40%).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a228728">\u000d\u000a                <title>Inheritance tax and trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>For IHT purposes, trusts broadly fall into two categories, which are discussed further\u000d\u000a                    below:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Trusts with a qualifying interest in possession</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>There are other categories of trust that don''t fall into these categories:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Bare trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            (the assets are treated as belonging to the beneficiary for tax purposes so no special\u000d\u000a                            trust rules apply).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Certain types of trust have preferential treatment for IHT purposes:</para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">trusts for bereaved minors</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    ;\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>certain\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">accumulation and maintenance trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    ; and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">18 to 25 trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    .\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <para>For more information on the IHT treatment of these types of trust, see<emphasis\u000d\u000a                                role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts: overview: How IHT applies to\u000d\u000a                            trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a417562">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Relevant property trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Relevant property trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        have their own IHT regime (most of the legislative provisions are found in<emphasis\u000d\u000a                            role="italic">Chapter III , Part III, IHTA 1984</emphasis>). Under this regime, an IHT\u000d\u000a                        charge can arise:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>When assets are given to the trust.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>On every ten-year anniversary of the creation of the trust.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>When capital is distributed to beneficiaries.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gift of assets to a relevant property trust is a chargeable lifetime transfer,\u000d\u000a                        triggering an immediate 20% charge to IHT. In addition, if the settlor fails to survive\u000d\u000a                        seven years from the date he gives assets to the trust, further IHT may be due.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Broadly, the rate of tax is up to 6% on each ten-year anniversary (charged on the value of\u000d\u000a                        the trust fund) and when capital is distributed from the trust (charged on the value of the\u000d\u000a                        distribution). For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Practice notes, Inheritance tax: relevant property trusts: key\u000d\u000a                            concepts\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax: relevant property trusts: calculating the charge\u000d\u000a                            to tax</emphasis>.<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts:\u000d\u000a                            overview: How IHT applies to trusts: relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The disclosure of tax avoidance schemes (DOTAS) regime includes IHT on lifetime transfers\u000d\u000a                        by individuals to relevant property trusts with effect from 6 April 2011. For further\u000d\u000a                        information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts: overview: How\u000d\u000a                            IHT applies to trusts: Relevant property trusts: Anti-avoidance measures</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a898484">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Trusts with a qualifying interest in possession</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Trusts with a\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">qualifying interest in possession</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        are taxed as though the beneficiary with the interest in possession (called the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">life tenant</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ) owns the trust assets (\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part III, IHTA 1984</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ). The trust is therefore taxed as though it forms part of the life tenant''s estate. Gifts\u000d\u000a                        to certain types of qualifying interest in possession trusts are<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            PETs</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts:\u000d\u000a                        overview: How IHT applies to trusts: qualifying IIP trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a812144">\u000d\u000a                <title>Inheritance tax and companies</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Although IHT relates to individuals, not companies, there are three areas where gifts to or\u000d\u000a                    from companies can result in an IHT charge:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts made by close companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">alteration of share capital</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            by close companies.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a742484">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to companies</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A gift to a company constitutes a chargeable lifetime transfer because it does not\u000d\u000a                        constitute a PET (<emphasis role="italic">section 7 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). This means\u000d\u000a                        that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is a lifetime charge to IHT at 20% on the value of the gift (strictly, the\u000d\u000a                                loss to the donor''s estate). This is subject to any available exemptions and reliefs\u000d\u000a                                and also to the donor''s available nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If the donor fails to survive for seven years from the date of the gift, the gift\u000d\u000a                                will become chargeable to IHT at 40%. Again, this is subject to any available\u000d\u000a                                exemptions and reliefs and with credit given for any IHT paid during lifetime. As\u000d\u000a                                with PETs, taper relief will be due if the donor survives for at least three years\u000d\u000a                                from the date of the gift (see<emphasis role="italic">Amount of tax charged depends\u000d\u000a                                    on how long the donor survives</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Unlike gifts to<emphasis role="italic">relevant property trusts</emphasis>, however, there\u000d\u000a                        are no ongoing IHT charges.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a597308">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts made by close companies</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Because IHT is payable by individuals and not companies, an anti-avoidance measure was\u000d\u000a                        introduced to stop individuals trying to avoid IHT by making gifts through private family\u000d\u000a                        companies.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where a gift is made by a\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">close company</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        , it is treated as having been made by the participators (<emphasis role="italic">Section 94\u000d\u000a                            , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). However, because it is only a "deemed" gift by the\u000d\u000a                        participators, it is not a PET and so there may be an immediate charge to IHT. Further, not\u000d\u000a                        all of the exemptions are available.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The following exemptions<emphasis role="bold">are</emphasis>available:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Annual</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 19(5) , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Spouse or civil partner</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 18 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Charities</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 23 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Political parties</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 24 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts of\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">land to housing associations</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 24A , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts for\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">national purposes</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 25 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The following exemptions are\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        available:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">small gifts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 20 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Normal gifts out of income</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 21 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">consideration of marriage</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 22 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>When a gift is made by a close company, any IHT is payable primarily by the company.\u000d\u000a                        However if the company does not pay, HMRC can go after the participators (except for those\u000d\u000a                        whose interest in the company is 5% or less) or the donee of the gift.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers: transfer\u000d\u000a                        of value by a close company</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a173416">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Alteration of share capital</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The participators of a close company are deemed to make a chargeable lifetime gift\u000d\u000a                        where:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is an alteration in, or extinguishment of, the company''s unquoted shares or\u000d\u000a                                loan capital.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is an alteration in, or extinguishment of, rights attaching to any shares\u000d\u000a                                in, or\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">debentures</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                of, that company which are unquoted.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Either of the above result in a reduction in the value of the participator''s\u000d\u000a                                estate.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 100 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>However, usual IHT principles apply, so there is no gift where the alteration is done for\u000d\u000a                        genuine commercial purposes and there is no gratuitous intent.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>As with gifts made by close companies, these are not PETs. The comments made\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">above</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        about exemptions therefore apply equally here.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers:\u000d\u000a                        alteration in the share capital of a close company</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a148485">\u000d\u000a                <title>Excluded property</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Certain types of property are excluded from IHT. In some cases the domicile status of the\u000d\u000a                    owner is not relevant and in other cases only non-UK domiciled individuals can benefit from the\u000d\u000a                    exemption.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a231157">\u000d\u000a                    <title>All individuals, regardless of domicile status</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        individuals (regardless of domicile), the following are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>A future interest in a trust (called a\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">reversionary interest</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                ), provided that:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>it was not purchased; and</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>neither the settlor (nor his spouse or civil partner) owns (or has ever\u000d\u000a                                        owned) the reversionary interest.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 48 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Decorations awarded for bravery (not purchased) (previously Extra Statutory\u000d\u000a                                Concession F19, now\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">section 6(1B)</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                of IHTA 1984). (See\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Legal update, Order made enacting extra-statutory\u000d\u000a                                    concessions\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                and<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC updates guidance on settlor-trustee\u000d\u000a                                    tax adjustments and awards for gallantry</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>An interest in an "excluded property" trust (unless it is an\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">interest in possession</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                purchased by a UK domiciled individual). Broadly, an excluded property trust is:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>a trust created by a settlor who was neither domiciled nor deemed\u000d\u000a                                        domiciled in the UK when he gave assets to it; and\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>which holds only non-UK assets.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <para>For information on the interaction between excluded property trusts and the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                rules, see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC confirms that excluded property\u000d\u000a                                    trumps reservation of benefit for non-dom trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a210614">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals not domiciled in the UK</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals who are\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        domiciled in the UK under general law (whether or not they are "deemed" domiciled for IHT\u000d\u000a                        purposes), exempt UK government securities are also excluded property.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a803400">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals domiciled in the Channel Islands or Isle of Man</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals domiciled in the Channel Islands or the Isle of Man (whether or not they\u000d\u000a                        are "deemed" domiciled for IHT purposes), the following additional assets are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">War savings certificates</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                .\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Premium bonds.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">National Savings and Investment</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                bank deposits.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a198610">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals neither domiciled nor deemed domiciled in the UK</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals who are neither domiciled nor deemed domiciled in the UK, the following\u000d\u000a                        additional assets are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any non-UK property.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Holdings in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">authorised unit trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                and shares in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">open ended investment companies</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (OEICs).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 6 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Property excluded from\u000d\u000a                        Inheritance Tax</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a347385">\u000d\u000a                <title>Exemptions available for both lifetime gifts and on death</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Gifts to certain favoured individuals or bodies are exempt from IHT (and do not use up the nil\u000d\u000a                    rate band). They are as follows:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to a<emphasis role="italic">spouse or civil partner</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">charities</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">political parties</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts of<emphasis role="italic">land to housing associations</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts for<emphasis role="italic">national purposes</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">heritage maintenance funds</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Transfers to employee trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a78580">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to a spouse or civil partner</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>IHT is not payable on any gift made between spouses or civil partners during lifetime or\u000d\u000a                        on death, provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Both parties are domiciled in the UK for IHT purposes (that is, they are either\u000d\u000a                                domiciled or deemed domiciled in the UK); or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Both parties are domiciled outside the UK for IHT purposes (that is, they are\u000d\u000a                                neither domiciled, nor deemed domiciled in the UK).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 18 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If one spouse or civil partner is domiciled in the UK for IHT purposes and the other is\u000d\u000a                        not, there is an upper limit to the spouse exemption in relation to gifts made to the non-UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse. The limit is \u00a355,000 overall, whether the gifts are made in lifetime or on\u000d\u000a                        death. This limit also applies when calculating the transferable nil rate band that can be\u000d\u000a                        claimed by the personal representatives of a non-UK domiciled spouse who is predeceased by a\u000d\u000a                        UK domiciled spouse.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The spouse exemption is available in full in relation to gifts made to the UK domiciled\u000d\u000a                        spouse.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A useful way to remember this is to consider the rationale. When assets pass from a UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse to a non-UK domiciled spouse, they are potentially leaving the IHT "net"\u000d\u000a                        forever (because the non-UK domiciled spouse may not be subject to IHT on his or her death).\u000d\u000a                        By limiting the spouse exemption in these circumstances, the lion''s share of IHT is secured\u000d\u000a                        on the first spouse''s death.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The government announced in its 2012 Budget on 21 March 2012 that it would publish a\u000d\u000a                        consultation document, with draft legislation, on its plans to increase the amount that a UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse or civil partner can give to his non-domiciled spouse or civil partner free\u000d\u000a                        from IHT. The legislation will form part of Finance Bill 2013. The consultation will propose\u000d\u000a                        an increase in the spouse exemption from \u00a355,000 to \u00a3325,000 that will then track any future\u000d\u000a                        increases in the nil rate band. There will also be an option for the non-domiciled spouse to\u000d\u000a                        elect to be treated as deemed domiciled so that they can benefit from the unlimited spouse\u000d\u000a                        exemption that gifts to UK-domiciled spouses and civil partners currently enjoy. It is now\u000d\u000a                        known that the consultation will be published in May 2012.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The government published draft legislation on 11 December 2012 to increase the amount that\u000d\u000a                        a UK domiciled individual can transfer to his non-UK domiciled spouse or civil partner free\u000d\u000a                        from IHT. The measure will raise the \u00a355,000 limit to the level of the prevailing IHT nil\u000d\u000a                        rate band. Non-UK domiciled individuals who have a UK domiciled spouse or civil partner will\u000d\u000a                        be able to elect to be treated as UK domiciled for IHT purposes. The legislation will have\u000d\u000a                        effect for transfers made on or after 6 April 2013.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information on the spouse exemption generally, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT\u000d\u000a                        Manual: Spouse or civil partner exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a71944">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to charities</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Outright gifts to UK, EU and Norwegian and Icelandic charities (or to charitable trusts\u000d\u000a                        from which only these charities may benefit) are exempt from IHT (<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            paragraph 1, Schedule 6, Finance Act 2010</emphasis>). For more information on the\u000d\u000a                        definition of charity for tax purposes see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, What is a\u000d\u000a                            charity: definition of charity for tax legislation</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information on the charity exemption for IHT, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT\u000d\u000a                        Manual: Charity exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on the reduced rate of IHT for estates of deceased individuals who leave\u000d\u000a                        10% or more of their net estate to charity, see<emphasis role="italic">The rate of\u000d\u000a                            tax</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a771967">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to political parties</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts to UK political parties are exempt, provided that the party is of sufficient\u000d\u000a                        stature. The requirements are that either of the following applied (as at the last general\u000d\u000a                        election):\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At least two members of the party were elected to the House of Commons.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At least one member of the party was so elected and at least 150,000 votes were\u000d\u000a                                given to candidates who were members of that party.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 24 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts to political\u000d\u000a                        parties</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a551704">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts of land to housing associations</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts of land to housing associations or to registered social landlords are exempt from\u000d\u000a                        IHT (<emphasis role="italic">section 24A , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts to registered housing\u000d\u000a                        associations</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a946913">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts for national purposes</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts for national purposes are exempt from IHT. The IHT legislation contains a list of\u000d\u000a                        bodies and institutions that are covered by this exemption. For example:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The National Gallery or British Museum or another national institution which\u000d\u000a                                exists wholly or mainly for the purpose of preserving a collection of scientific,\u000d\u000a                                historic or artistic interest for the public benefit.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any museum or art gallery in the UK which exists wholly or mainly for the purpose\u000d\u000a                                stated above.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any library, the main function of which is to serve the needs of teaching and\u000d\u000a                                research at a university in the UK.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 25 and Schedule 3 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts for National\u000d\u000a                        Purposes</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In the 2011 Budget, the government announced that it would consult on a proposal to\u000d\u000a                        introduce a tax reduction for taxpayers who give a work of art or historical object of\u000d\u000a                        national importance to the State. The consultation ran from 29 June 2011 to 21 September\u000d\u000a                        2011. On 6 December 2011, the government published draft legislation for inclusion in the\u000d\u000a                        Finance Bill 2012. For further information on this measure and to follow its progress\u000d\u000a                        towards implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker\u000d\u000a                            2011-12: Tax reduction for gifts of art to the nation</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a761286">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to heritage maintenance funds</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Heritage maintenance funds are trusts that maintain historic buildings or land of scenic,\u000d\u000a                        scientific or historic interest. A gift to a heritage maintenance fund is exempt from IHT.\u000d\u000a                        The fund does not incur any ongoing IHT charges as long as it meets the following\u000d\u000a                        conditions:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The trustees must:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>be approved by the Treasury;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>contain at least one trustee from a requisite professional body; and\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>must be resident in the UK when HMRC give their direction as to whether\u000d\u000a                                        the trust qualifies.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The fund must be used (for a minimum period of six years from the date it was\u000d\u000a                                given to the trust) for:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>the maintenance, repair or preservation of the heritage property;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>other charities that exist for such purposes;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>making provision for public access to the heritage property; or</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>national purposes (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts for national\u000d\u000a                                        purposes</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 27 and Schedule 4 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>HMRC determines whether the building or land is sufficiently important to merit the\u000d\u000a                        exemption (see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax: conditional exemption\u000d\u000a                            for heritage property: What constitutes heritage property?</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Exemptions: maintenance funds (paragraph IHTM11250)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Capital Taxation and the National Heritage (September 2011)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (Chapter 8).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a583748">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Transfers to employee trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A transfer of shares by an individual to an\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">employee benefit trust</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (EBT) is exempt provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The shares are held:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>on trust for the benefit of all or most of the employees or office holders\u000d\u000a                                        of the company; or\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>under an approved profit sharing scheme or share incentive plan.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At the time of (or within one year of) the transfer, the trustees hold more than\u000d\u000a                                half of the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">ordinary shares</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                in the company and have voting control on all questions affecting the company as a\u000d\u000a                                whole.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The trust cannot be used to benefit any shareholder who is entitled to:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>5% or more of any class of shares in the company; or</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>5% or more of its assets on winding up.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 28 , IHTA 1984.</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Employee Benefit Trusts (from\u000d\u000a                        IHTM42900)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on the IHT issues that arise where an EBT is established by a close\u000d\u000a                        company, see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC publishes guidance on taxation of\u000d\u000a                            EBTs</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on EBTs generally, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Trusts in\u000d\u000a                        commercial transactions: Employee benefit trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a563285">\u000d\u000a                <title>Exemptions available for lifetime gifts only</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Additional exemptions are also available for lifetime gifts, if none of the above exemptions\u000d\u000a                    apply. The most commonly used exemptions are as follows:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Normal expenditure out of income</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Small gifts to any one person</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Wedding and civil partnership gifts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Annual exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Note that the "normal expenditure out of income" exemption is applied first and the "annual"\u000d\u000a                    exemption is applied last, after all the other exemptions.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a86671">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Normal expenditure out of income</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts are exempt if they form part of the donor''s normal expenditure out of\u000d\u000a                        (after tax) income, provided that the donor is left with sufficient income to maintain his\u000d\u000a                        usual standard of living (<emphasis role="italic">section 21 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A regular pattern of giving is required, for example meeting annual school fees for a\u000d\u000a                        grandchild or paying the premiums on a life policy for another''s benefit.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The first gift in a series can qualify, provided further gifts are intended. If the donor\u000d\u000a                        dies before making the second gift, there must be sufficient evidence that he intended to\u000d\u000a                        make a series of gifts.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Normal expenditure out of\u000d\u000a                        income</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a516515">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Small gifts to any one person</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts of up to \u00a3250 to any one individual during a tax year are exempt (<emphasis\u000d\u000a                            role="italic">section 20 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). The exemption is only available if the\u000d\u000a                        gift (or gifts) to that individual does not exceed \u00a3250 in total. It is not possible to\u000d\u000a                        carry forward any unused portion to the next tax year.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, an individual makes a number of gifts to the same individual during a tax\u000d\u000a                        year and the gifts total \u00a3300. The small gifts exemption does not apply to any part of the\u000d\u000a                        gift(s).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Specific lifetime exemptions:\u000d\u000a                        small gifts exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a758140">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Wedding and civil partnership gifts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts on the occasion of a marriage or registration of a civil partnership are\u000d\u000a                        exempt up to certain limits (<emphasis role="italic">section 22 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). The\u000d\u000a                        amount of the limit depends on the relationship of the donor to the couple, as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Each parent can give \u00a35,000.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Each grandparent (or remoter ancestor) can give \u00a32,500.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Either of the couple can give to each other \u00a32,500.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any other person can give \u00a31,000.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gifts can be made to either party of the marriage or civil partnership, or to the\u000d\u000a                        couple jointly. The gifts can be outright, or in trust (provided that only the couple, their\u000d\u000a                        issue and certain other close family members can benefit).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gift must take place on or before the ceremony and must be conditional on the ceremony\u000d\u000a                        taking place. The exemption is not available if the ceremony does not take place.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts made in consideration of marriage or registration\u000d\u000a                            of civil partnership .\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a676734">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Annual exemption</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts (which do not fall into any other exemption) are exempt up to \u00a33,000 a\u000d\u000a                        year. If the annual exemption is (wholly or partly) unused for a particular tax year, the\u000d\u000a                        unused portion may be carried forward for one tax year only. (<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            Section 19 , IHTA 1984.</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Annual exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a1033263">\u000d\u000a                <title>Potentially exempt transfers</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>A potentially exempt transfer (PET) can be made by an individual. If there are no other\u000d\u000a                    exemptions available, the PET might eventually fall out of charge. PETs are:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Outright gifts to individuals.</para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">disabled person''s interests</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            .\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>When an\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">immediate post-death interest</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            comes to an end and the continuing trust qualifies as a\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">trust for bereaved minors</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            .\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a740822">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Amount of tax charged depends on how long the donor survives</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>PETs are called "potentially" exempt, because if the donor survives for seven years from\u000d\u000a                        the date of the gift, the gift becomes fully exempt.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If the donor fails to survive for seven years, the gift becomes chargeable and will use up\u000d\u000a                        all or part of the donor''s nil rate band. However, the longer the donor survives after\u000d\u000a                        making the gift (subject to surviving at least three years), the lower the IHT. This relief\u000d\u000a                        is called "taper relief" and will be calculated as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <table frame="all">\u000d\u000a                            <tgroup cols="2">\u000d\u000a                                <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="50%"/>\u000d\u000a                                <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="50%"/>\u000d\u000a                                <tbody>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                                <emphasis role="bold">Period between the date of gift and the death\u000d\u000a                                                    of the donor\u000d\u000a                                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                            </para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                                <emphasis role="bold">Rate of taper relief (applied to the amount of\u000d\u000a                                                    IHT)\u000d\u000a                                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                            </para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>0-3 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>0%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>3-4 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>20%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>4-5 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>40%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>5-6 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>60%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>6-7 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>80%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>7 years and over</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>100%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                </tbody>\u000d\u000a                            </tgroup>\u000d\u000a                        </table>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 7(4) , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The taper relief is applied to the IHT due,\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        the value of the gift. As result, the full value of the gift (calculated as the "loss to the\u000d\u000a                        donor") uses up all or part of the nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Zeb makes a gift of \u00a3400,000 to his son Charlie on 1 April 1998. He made no\u000d\u000a                        other gifts during his lifetime. Zeb dies on 5 March 2002. Because Zeb has failed to survive\u000d\u000a                        for at least seven years from the date of the gift (and as the gift exceeds Zeb''s nil rate\u000d\u000a                        band), IHT will be payable on the gift, calculated as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para xml:space="preserve">Value of the gift (strictly, the loss to Zeb''s estate): \u00a3400,000.\u000d\u000aLess two annual exemptions (see <emphasis role="italic">  Annual exemption  </emphasis>): \u00a36,000.\u000d\u000aLess the nil rate band on 5 March 2002 (see <emphasis role="italic">  The nil rate band  </emphasis>): \u00a3242,000.\u000d\u000aChargeable value of the gift: \u00a3152,000.</para><para xml:space="preserve">IHT @ 40%: \u00a360,800.\u000d\u000aLess taper relief at 20%: \u00a312,160.\u000d\u000aIHT due on the gift: \u00a348,640.</para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers: what is a potentially exempt\u000d\u000a                            transfer?\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a981403">\u000d\u000a                <title>10% reduction in rate of inheritance tax for gifts to charity</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The Finance Act Bill 2012 (F A B 2012) introduce d s a lower death rate of IHT for testators\u000d\u000a                    who leave 10% or more of their net estates to charity (clause 207 and Schedule 32, FB 2012) .\u000d\u000a                    The lower rate of IHT is will be 36%, instead of 40%. The lower rate applies will apply in\u000d\u000a                    relation to the estates of testators who die on or after 6 April 2012 (paragraph 10, Schedule\u000d\u000a                    32, FB 2012) . This will be before FB 2012 receives Royal Assent (probably in July 2012). For\u000d\u000a                    more information on the 10% reduction in IHT, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                        Inheritance tax: leaving 10% of an estate to charity</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a819637">\u000d\u000a                <title>Relief from inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>If the gift is of a certain type of asset, relief may apply to reduce the amount of IHT\u000d\u000a                    payable, sometimes to nil.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The following reliefs apply automatically:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Agricultural property relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Claims for the following reliefs must be specifically made within two years of the death (or\u000d\u000a                    lifetime gift):\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Woodlands relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">National heritage property - conditional exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>The reliefs are available both for lifetime gifts and on death,\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">except</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    for woodlands relief, which is only available on<emphasis role="bold">death</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a317615">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Business property relief (BPR)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where the conditions are met:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>100% relief is available for:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>unquoted share-holdings;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>interests in a business (whether owned as a sole trade or in\u000d\u000a                                        partnership).\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>50% relief is available for:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>shares in a quoted company (where the donor had control of the company);\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>assets, such as land and buildings, used by the donor''s partnership or\u000d\u000a                                        company.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter I , Part V, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Generally, the donor must have owned the shares or the business for at least two years\u000d\u000a                        prior to the gift or death. Further, certain types of activities and investments are\u000d\u000a                        excluded from relief. For example, relief is not available if the business or company''s\u000d\u000a                        activities consist mainly in dealing in securities, stocks or shares, land or buildings, or\u000d\u000a                        making or holding investments.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC''s guidance on business property relief, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual:\u000d\u000a                        Business relief and businesses (from paragraph IHTM25000)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a89262">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Agricultural property relief (APR)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where the conditions are met, agricultural property may benefit from relief at 100% or 50%\u000d\u000a                        (depending on who farms the land and how long the land has been owned). Relief is given on\u000d\u000a                        the agricultural value of the land. (<emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part V, IHTA\u000d\u000a                            1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        may also be available (after agricultural property relief has been given), for example,\u000d\u000a                        where a farmer owns the land and farms it as a business.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For further information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax agricultural property relief:\u000d\u000a                            overview\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Agricultural relief (from paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM24000)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a620983">\u000d\u000a                    <title>National heritage property - conditional exemption</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where property and assets are important to the UK''s national heritage, IHT can be\u000d\u000a                        deferred, provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>A claim is made within two years of the gift or death.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The recipient of the asset gives an undertaking to allow public access and to\u000d\u000a                                preserve it.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part II, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The relief is available for both lifetime gifts and on death, although if a lifetime gift,\u000d\u000a                        the property must have been:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Owned by the donor (or his spouse or civil partner) throughout the six-year period\u000d\u000a                                before the gift; or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Inherited (at any time, even within the six-year period before the gift) and a\u000d\u000a                                conditional exemption applied when inherited.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>An IHT charge arises if the undertakings are broken or the recipient disposes of the\u000d\u000a                        property. If the recipient keeps to the undertakings, heritage property can pass down from\u000d\u000a                        generation to generation without any charge to IHT.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax:\u000d\u000a                        conditional exemption for heritage property</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC guidance, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Heritage property (from\u000d\u000a                        paragraph IHTM04111)</emphasis>,\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Exemptions - conditional exemption (paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM11260)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Capital Taxation and the National Heritage (September 2011)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (Chapters 4 - 7).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a788464">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Woodlands relief (on death)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodland may qualify for:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para><emphasis role="italic">Agricultural property relief</emphasis>, if it is\u000d\u000a                                ancillary to farmland.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para><emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>, if it is commercial\u000d\u000a                                woodland.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If neither of these reliefs apply, woodlands relief might be available.</para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodlands relief is only available on death and operates as an IHT deferral. Where the\u000d\u000a                        conditions are met, an election can be made to exclude the value of the timber (but not the\u000d\u000a                        land) from the value of the estate for IHT. When the timber is sold (or given away), the\u000d\u000a                        sale proceeds (or the market value at the date of the gift) is charged to IHT. The election\u000d\u000a                        must be made within two years of death.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodlands relief is available where:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The deceased owned an interest in the land on which the timber has been growing\u000d\u000a                                (either outright or through a qualifying interest in possession) for at least five\u000d\u000a                                years; or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The deceased received the interest in the land by gift or inheritance at any time\u000d\u000a                                (including within the five years before death).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter III , Part V, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Care needs to be taken before making an election for woodlands relief, because IHT will be\u000d\u000a                        payable on the future sale proceeds (or the market value of the timber, if given away). If\u000d\u000a                        the timber is not worth very much on death (for example, because the trees are still very\u000d\u000a                        young) it would be better\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        to make the election and to pay the IHT instead.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC guidance, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Woodlands (from paragraph\u000d\u000a                        IHTM04371)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <section3 id="a993114">\u000d\u000a                        <title>EU law</title>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Following the European Court of Justice (ECJ) case\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Theodor J\u00e4ger v Finanzamt Kusel-Landstuhl (Case C-256/06,\u000d\u000a                                European Court reports 2008)\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            and the European Commission''s formal request to the UK to change its legislation in\u000d\u000a                            relation to APR and woodlands relief (see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, European\u000d\u000a                                Commission asks UK to amend inheritance tax legislation</emphasis>), the\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Finance Act 2009</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            extended the scope of APR and woodlands relief to property within the European Economic\u000d\u000a                            Area. See<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2008-09:\u000d\u000a                                Agricultural property relief and woodlands</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </section3>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a414325">\u000d\u000a                <title>Anti-avoidance measures</title>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a825995">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts with reservation of benefit</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In order for a lifetime gift to be fully effective for IHT purposes, the donor must give\u000d\u000a                        the property away without any strings attached. If the donor retains a significant benefit\u000d\u000a                        or enjoyment in the property given away, it will remain part of his or her estate for the\u000d\u000a                        purposes of calculating IHT. These gifts are called\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (GROBs).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Judy gives her home to her three adult children who live elsewhere. She\u000d\u000a                        transfers the legal title into their joint names.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Judy continues to live at the property rent-free, this is a GROB and the\u000d\u000a                                property remains in her estate for IHT purposes.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Judy releases her reservation (for example, by moving out or by paying her\u000d\u000a                                children full market rent), this will be a deemed<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    PET</emphasis>. Provided Judy survives for seven complete years after releasing\u000d\u000a                                the reservation of benefit, the deemed PET will be exempt from IHT.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The rule is that the property must be enjoyed to the "virtual exclusion" of the donor. As\u000d\u000a                        a result, there is some scope for a very minor reservation of benefit. Examples are set out\u000d\u000a                        in\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: The reservation: exclusion of the donor (paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM14333)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and include the following scenarios:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The donor pays social visits or stays temporarily at a house given away.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The donor is given the occasional lift in a car given away.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>These anti-avoidance provisions are found in\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">section 102</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        of the<emphasis role="italic">Finance Act 1986</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In addition, there is no GROB where the gift is exempt from IHT, for example gifts to a\u000d\u000a                        spouse or civil partner (see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Exemptions available for both lifetime gifts and on death</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Exemptions available for lifetime gifts only</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a158451">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Pre-owned assets</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The GROB provisions were intended to prevent artificial avoidance of IHT by exploiting\u000d\u000a                        loopholes in the legislation. They have not been totally successful, as many schemes\u000d\u000a                        (usually involving houses or chattels) were created to get round the provisions (one example\u000d\u000a                        is the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">home loan scheme</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ). To combat this, the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">pre-owned assets charge</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (POAC) was introduced with effect from 6 April 2005.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Broadly, POAC applies where an individual gives away property (for example land and\u000d\u000a                        buildings, chattels or money and investments) and subsequently benefits from that property\u000d\u000a                        (or property derived from it). If caught, an annual income tax charge is imposed on the\u000d\u000a                        donor in relation to the benefit he receives from the property, unless he elects for the\u000d\u000a                        gift to be taxed as a GROB. The election must be made by the 31 January following the tax\u000d\u000a                        year in which the individual first becomes liable to POAC. (\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Section 84 and Schedule 15 , Finance Act 2004</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Chapter 8 , Part 5, Income Tax (Trading and Other Income) Act\u000d\u000a                            2005</emphasis>.) For HMRC''s guidance on this matter, including late elections, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: IHT manual: Pre-owned assets: Election into inheritance tax\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">see</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        .\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Income tax and pre-owned assets: detailed guidance: Section 3\u000d\u000a                            - The election into Inheritance Tax\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        .\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>There are a number of exclusions and exemptions; however the broad principles are as\u000d\u000a                        follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Property which is subject to IHT in the hands of the donor (for example, property\u000d\u000a                                in which he has reserved a benefit) should not be subject to POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Property which is not subject to IHT because it qualifies for favoured IHT\u000d\u000a                                treatment (for example, because it benefits from an exemption or relief, such as the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">spouse exemption</emphasis>), should not be subject to POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any other property which has been given away, and from which the donor derives a\u000d\u000a                                benefit, should be caught by POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For full details of HMRC''s guidance on POAC, see<emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Income tax\u000d\u000a                        and pre-owned assets: detailed guidance</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a        </fulltext>\u000d\u000a    </practicenote>\u000d\u000a</xml>\u000d\u000a','2013-03-15 00:00:00.000000','xopus')
INSERT INTO ARTICLE VALUES(2,0,1,'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\u000d\u000a<xml>\u000d\u000a    <practicenote>\u000d\u000a        <metadata>\u000d\u000a            <revhistory>\u000d\u000a                <revision>\u000d\u000a                    <revtitle>Finance Bill 2012</revtitle>\u000d\u000a                    <date>7 July 2012</date>\u000d\u000a                    <author>PLC Private Client</author>\u000d\u000a                    <revdescription>\u000d\u000a                        <section1 id="a724509">\u000d\u000a                            <para>We have updated this practice note to reflect the draft clauses included in the\u000d\u000a                                Finance Bill 2012 amd the announcement in the Budget on 21 March 2012 of two\u000d\u000a                                consultations to be published in July 2012. We have also included an additional\u000d\u000a                                section on the reduction in the rate of IHT for gifts of 10% or more of the net\u000d\u000a                                estate to charity.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </section1>\u000d\u000a                    </revdescription>\u000d\u000a                </revision>\u000d\u000a                <revision>\u000d\u000a                    <revtitle>Budget 2009: APR and woodlands relief extended to property within the EEA</revtitle>\u000d\u000a                    <date>23-Apr-2009</date>\u000d\u000a                    <author>PLC Private Client</author>\u000d\u000a                    <revdescription>\u000d\u000a                        <section1 id="a410603">\u000d\u000a                            <para>This practice note has been amended to reflect the fact that on 22 April 2009, the\u000d\u000a                                Chancellor announced that APR and woodlands relief will be extended to cover\u000d\u000a                                property within the European Economic Area (EEA), following the European\u000d\u000a                                Commission''s formal request to the UK to change the legislation.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </section1>\u000d\u000a                    </revdescription>\u000d\u000a                </revision>\u000d\u000a            </revhistory>\u000d\u000a        </metadata>\u000d\u000a        <fulltext>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a882719">\u000d\u000a                <title>Introduction to inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Inheritance tax (IHT) is primarily a charge on an individual''s\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">estate</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    on death. However, it can also arise on certain lifetime gifts, for example:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to certain trusts (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts:\u000d\u000a                            relevant property trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to companies (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts involving close companies (see\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Gifts made by close companies</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            and<emphasis role="italic">Alteration of share capital</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Ongoing IHT charges can also arise on trust property under the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">relevant property regime</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property regime</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In addition, IHT may be payable on outright gifts made within seven years of an individual''s\u000d\u000a                    death. This is mainly to catch those who try to avoid an IHT charge by giving away their estate\u000d\u000a                    shortly before they die. These are called\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (PETs) (see<emphasis role="italic">Potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The word "gift" is not used in the IHT legislation, although it is used in this note for ease.\u000d\u000a                    The legislation actually uses defined terms such as "disposition", "transfer of value" and\u000d\u000a                    "chargeable transfer", which cover a wide range of circumstances not always immediately\u000d\u000a                    recognised as being "gifts". The purpose is to cover lifetime transactions that result in a loss\u000d\u000a                    to the donor''s estate (and an increase in the donee''s estate), unless the transaction is for\u000d\u000a                    genuine commercial reasons and there is no gratuitous intent.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The legislation does not only cover gifts of cash or specific assets. It also covers, for\u000d\u000a                    example, sales of assets (for less than their full market value) to certain family members,\u000d\u000a                    fixed-term interest free loans and the rent-free use of property. There are also specific types\u000d\u000a                    of "excluded property" which fall outside the scope of the IHT legislation.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Every individual has a nil rate band in which IHT is charged at 0% (see<emphasis\u000d\u000a                        role="italic">The nil rate band</emphasis>). In addition to this, there are allowances,\u000d\u000a                    exemptions and reliefs which reduce the amount of IHT payable, if certain conditions are met.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The IHT legislation is contained in the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">Inheritance Tax Act 1984</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (IHTA 1984).\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">HM Revenue &amp; Customs</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (HMRC) have published detailed guidance on this topic, which is contained in\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Inheritance Tax Manual</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (IHT manual).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a609034">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Future review?</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>On 3 March 2011, the Office of Tax Simplification (OTS) published a final report on its\u000d\u000a                        tax reliefs review, which was commissioned by the Coalition government in November 2010. In\u000d\u000a                        its report, the OTS recommended that IHT reliefs be reviewed in the context of a separate\u000d\u000a                        review of IHT as a whole and that any review of IHT must include a review of the taxation of\u000d\u000a                        trusts (see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, Final report on tax reliefs review: private\u000d\u000a                            client exemptions and reliefs: Reliefs to be reviewed separately</emphasis>). For the\u000d\u000a                        latest information on the OTS review of tax reliefs and the government''s response to the\u000d\u000a                        review, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2011-12: Office of\u000d\u000a                            Tax Simplification reviews</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>HMRC published a The government announced, in its Budget on 21 March 2012, that it will p\u000d\u000a                        ublish a consultation document in July 2012 on its plans to simplify the way IHT is\u000d\u000a                        calculated for ten yearly charges and exit charges in<emphasis role="italic">relevant\u000d\u000a                            property trusts</emphasis>. The month set for publication is now known to be July 2012.\u000d\u000a                        It will publish a further consultation on these reforms in the spring of 2013. To follow the\u000d\u000a                        outcome of the consultation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client legislation tracker\u000d\u000a                            2012-13: IHT: simplifying calculations for relevant property trusts</emphasis>. For more\u000d\u000a                        information on how relevant property trusts are currently taxed, see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            Relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a724773">\u000d\u000a                <title>Territorial scope of inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The extent to which an individual is charged to IHT depends on their\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">domicile</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    status:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An individual who is domiciled in the UK is subject to IHT on their worldwide\u000d\u000a                            estate.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An individual who is not domiciled in the UK is subject to IHT only on their UK\u000d\u000a                            estate.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>"Domicile" is a complex concept which is based on a long line of cases in the field of\u000d\u000a                    international law. It has been incorporated into the IHT legislation as a means of reducing\u000d\u000a                    exposure to IHT for those who have only a temporary link with the UK.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In this context, domicile has a specific legal meaning, beyond the simple dictionary\u000d\u000a                    definition of "place of residence". An individual can be resident in the UK for many years and\u000d\u000a                    yet be domiciled elsewhere. In certain (more unusual) circumstances, an individual can also be\u000d\u000a                    domiciled in the UK without having set foot here. For further information on domicile, see\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Domicile</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>In addition, Parliament decided that certain individuals should be subject to IHT on their\u000d\u000a                    worldwide estate, even though they are not domiciled in the UK under the general law. The\u000d\u000a                    rationale for this is that they have lived in the UK for a long time and should therefore\u000d\u000a                    contribute more tax. The following individuals are "deemed domiciled" in the UK for IHT\u000d\u000a                    purposes:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Individuals who have lived in the UK for at least 17 out of the previous 20 tax years.\u000d\u000a                            These individuals will be "deemed domiciled" in the UK from the start of their 17th tax\u000d\u000a                            year of residence.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>UK domiciled individuals who leave the UK and acquire a new domicile abroad. These\u000d\u000a                            individuals will be "deemed domiciled" for three years following the date they acquired\u000d\u000a                            their new domicile.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 267 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Examples of how these rules work can be found in<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Domicile: Deemed domicile</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a244616">\u000d\u000a                <title>The charge to tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Broadly, IHT is charged as follows:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="bold">On death</emphasis>, in relation to a deceased person''s estate.\u000d\u000a                            This includes:\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>gifts made in the seven years prior to death (see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    Potentially exempt transfers</emphasis>); and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="bold">On chargeable lifetime gifts</emphasis>. For example:\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts by close companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>An\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">alteration of share capital</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    by close companies.\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">On trust property under the relevant property regime</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            (see<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property\u000d\u000a                            trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a460375">\u000d\u000a                <title>The rate of tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>IHT is charged at the following rates:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>On the\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">nil rate band</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            amount, the rate of tax is 0% (that is, there is no IHT to pay).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>On the balance, the rate of tax is:</para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>20% for chargeable lifetime gifts (see<emphasis role="italic">The charge to\u000d\u000a                                    tax</emphasis>); and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>40% on estates on death (or 36% where 10% or more of the net estate is given\u000d\u000a                                    to charity, see<emphasis role="italic">10% reduction in rate of inheritance tax\u000d\u000a                                        for gifts to charity</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 7 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Relevant property trusts have their own charging regime (see<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                    Inheritance tax and trusts: relevant property trusts</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For more information on IHT rates and allowances, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Tax data for individuals and trustees</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>Paragraph 207 and Schedule 32 of the Finance Bill 2012 provide for the application of a\u000d\u000a                    reduced rate of IHT to the estates of deceased individuals who leave 10% or more of their net\u000d\u000a                    estate to charity. For further information on this measure, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice\u000d\u000a                        note, Inheritance tax: leaving 10% of an estate to charity</emphasis>. To follow the\u000d\u000a                    progress of the measure towards implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax\u000d\u000a                        legislation tracker 2011-12: IHT: reduced rate for charitable testators</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a938367">\u000d\u000a                <title>The nil rate band</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The nil rate band is so called, because it is the amount which is chargeable to IHT at 0%.\u000d\u000a                    Each individual currently has a maximum nil rate band amount of \u00a3325,000 . It was announced in\u000d\u000a                    the 2009 Budget that the nil rate band amount would be frozen at \u00a3325,000 until 5 February 2015.\u000d\u000a                    , which is frozen until 5 April 2015 (see<emphasis role="italic">June 2010 Budget: key private\u000d\u000a                        client tax announcements: IHT nil rate band to remain frozen at \u00a3325,000 until 5 April\u000d\u000a                        2015</emphasis>) . The Secretary of State for Health, Jeremy Hunt, announced on 11 February\u000d\u000a                    2013 that the nil rate band would be frozen at this level for a further three years from 2015-16\u000d\u000a                    to meet part of the costs of changes to the funding of social care.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>This is the maximum amount, because the nil rate band can be used up in lifetime by:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Chargeable lifetime gifts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">PETs</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            made within the seven years before death.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>In the 2011 Budget, the government announced that from 2015-16, the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">consumer prices index</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (CPI) would be used as the "default indexation assumption" for the nil rate band, instead of the\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">retail prices index</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    (RPI). Draft legislation was published on 6 December 2011 for inclusion in the Finance Bill\u000d\u000a                    2012. The draft legislation provides for automatic indexation of the nil rate band each year,\u000d\u000a                    using the CPI over the year to the previous September, although this may be overridden for a tax\u000d\u000a                    year if Parliament sets a different figure. To follow the progress of this measure towards\u000d\u000a                    implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2011-12: IHT:\u000d\u000a                        CPI indexation of nil rate band</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For further information about the nil rate band, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Inheritance tax transferable nil rate band: overview</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For historic nil rate band amounts, see<emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Inheritance Tax\u000d\u000a                    thresholds</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>For more information on IHT rates and allowances, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                    Tax data for individuals and trustees</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a654920">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Surviving spouse or civil partner can inherit unused portion of nil rate band</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>As a result of a change introduced by the<emphasis role="italic">Finance Act\u000d\u000a                        2008</emphasis>, a surviving spouse or\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">civil partner</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (who dies on or after 9 October 2007) can now effectively "inherit" the unused percentage of\u000d\u000a                        their deceased spouse or partner''s nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Jermaine dies in September 2007 and, on death, has assets of \u00a3500,000. His\u000d\u000a                        nil rate band of \u00a3300,000 is fully intact. He leaves a \u00a375,000 legacy to his daughter Dot,\u000d\u000a                        and the remainder of his estate to his wife Marnie.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>No IHT is payable on the assets passing to Marnie, because of the spouse exemption\u000d\u000a                                (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts to a spouse or civil partner</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>No IHT is payable on the legacy to Dot because it falls within Jermaine''s nil rate\u000d\u000a                                band.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Jermaine has essentially "wasted" 75% of his nil rate band.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>On Marnie''s death in September 2008, she has assets of \u00a3600,000 in her estate. Her nil\u000d\u000a                        rate band of \u00a3312,000 is fully intact. She leaves everything to Dot.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Marnie had died before 9 October 2007, the IHT payable on her estate would have\u000d\u000a                                been \u00a3115,200 (\u00a3600,000 - \u00a3312,000 x 40%).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Since she died after that date, the Finance Act 2008 will apply. Because Jermaine\u000d\u000a                                did not use 75% of his nil rate band, Marnie''s executors can claim an additional 75%\u000d\u000a                                of the nil rate band amount in force at the date of her death. Her "uplifted" nil\u000d\u000a                                rate band is therefore \u00a3546,000 (\u00a3312,000 + \u00a3234,000). The IHT payable on her death\u000d\u000a                                is therefore \u00a321,600 (\u00a3600,000 - \u00a3546,000 x 40%).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a228728">\u000d\u000a                <title>Inheritance tax and trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>For IHT purposes, trusts broadly fall into two categories, which are discussed further\u000d\u000a                    below:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Trusts with a qualifying interest in possession</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>There are other categories of trust that don''t fall into these categories:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Bare trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            (the assets are treated as belonging to the beneficiary for tax purposes so no special\u000d\u000a                            trust rules apply).\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Certain types of trust have preferential treatment for IHT purposes:</para>\u000d\u000a                        <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">trusts for bereaved minors</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    ;\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>certain\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">accumulation and maintenance trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    ; and\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <para>\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                        <emphasis role="italic">18 to 25 trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                    .\u000d\u000a                                </para>\u000d\u000a                            </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <para>For more information on the IHT treatment of these types of trust, see<emphasis\u000d\u000a                                role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts: overview: How IHT applies to\u000d\u000a                            trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a417562">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Relevant property trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Relevant property trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        have their own IHT regime (most of the legislative provisions are found in<emphasis\u000d\u000a                            role="italic">Chapter III , Part III, IHTA 1984</emphasis>). Under this regime, an IHT\u000d\u000a                        charge can arise:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>When assets are given to the trust.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>On every ten-year anniversary of the creation of the trust.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>When capital is distributed to beneficiaries.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gift of assets to a relevant property trust is a chargeable lifetime transfer,\u000d\u000a                        triggering an immediate 20% charge to IHT. In addition, if the settlor fails to survive\u000d\u000a                        seven years from the date he gives assets to the trust, further IHT may be due.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Broadly, the rate of tax is up to 6% on each ten-year anniversary (charged on the value of\u000d\u000a                        the trust fund) and when capital is distributed from the trust (charged on the value of the\u000d\u000a                        distribution). For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Practice notes, Inheritance tax: relevant property trusts: key\u000d\u000a                            concepts\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Inheritance tax: relevant property trusts: calculating the charge\u000d\u000a                            to tax</emphasis>.<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts:\u000d\u000a                            overview: How IHT applies to trusts: relevant property trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The disclosure of tax avoidance schemes (DOTAS) regime includes IHT on lifetime transfers\u000d\u000a                        by individuals to relevant property trusts with effect from 6 April 2011. For further\u000d\u000a                        information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts: overview: How\u000d\u000a                            IHT applies to trusts: Relevant property trusts: Anti-avoidance measures</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a898484">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Trusts with a qualifying interest in possession</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Trusts with a\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">qualifying interest in possession</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        are taxed as though the beneficiary with the interest in possession (called the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">life tenant</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ) owns the trust assets (\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part III, IHTA 1984</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ). The trust is therefore taxed as though it forms part of the life tenant''s estate. Gifts\u000d\u000a                        to certain types of qualifying interest in possession trusts are<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            PETs</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Taxation of UK trusts:\u000d\u000a                        overview: How IHT applies to trusts: qualifying IIP trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a812144">\u000d\u000a                <title>Inheritance tax and companies</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Although IHT relates to individuals, not companies, there are three areas where gifts to or\u000d\u000a                    from companies can result in an IHT charge:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts to companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Gifts made by close companies</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>An\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">alteration of share capital</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            by close companies.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a742484">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to companies</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A gift to a company constitutes a chargeable lifetime transfer because it does not\u000d\u000a                        constitute a PET (<emphasis role="italic">section 7 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). This means\u000d\u000a                        that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is a lifetime charge to IHT at 20% on the value of the gift (strictly, the\u000d\u000a                                loss to the donor''s estate). This is subject to any available exemptions and reliefs\u000d\u000a                                and also to the donor''s available nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If the donor fails to survive for seven years from the date of the gift, the gift\u000d\u000a                                will become chargeable to IHT at 40%. Again, this is subject to any available\u000d\u000a                                exemptions and reliefs and with credit given for any IHT paid during lifetime. As\u000d\u000a                                with PETs, taper relief will be due if the donor survives for at least three years\u000d\u000a                                from the date of the gift (see<emphasis role="italic">Amount of tax charged depends\u000d\u000a                                    on how long the donor survives</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Unlike gifts to<emphasis role="italic">relevant property trusts</emphasis>, however, there\u000d\u000a                        are no ongoing IHT charges.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a597308">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts made by close companies</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Because IHT is payable by individuals and not companies, an anti-avoidance measure was\u000d\u000a                        introduced to stop individuals trying to avoid IHT by making gifts through private family\u000d\u000a                        companies.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where a gift is made by a\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">close company</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        , it is treated as having been made by the participators (<emphasis role="italic">Section 94\u000d\u000a                            , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). However, because it is only a "deemed" gift by the\u000d\u000a                        participators, it is not a PET and so there may be an immediate charge to IHT. Further, not\u000d\u000a                        all of the exemptions are available.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The following exemptions<emphasis role="bold">are</emphasis>available:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Annual</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 19(5) , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Spouse or civil partner</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 18 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Charities</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 23 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Political parties</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 24 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts of\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">land to housing associations</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 24A , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts for\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">national purposes</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 25 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The following exemptions are\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        available:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">small gifts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                exemption (<emphasis role="italic">section 20 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Normal gifts out of income</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 21 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Gifts in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">consideration of marriage</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (<emphasis role="italic">section 22 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>When a gift is made by a close company, any IHT is payable primarily by the company.\u000d\u000a                        However if the company does not pay, HMRC can go after the participators (except for those\u000d\u000a                        whose interest in the company is 5% or less) or the donee of the gift.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers: transfer\u000d\u000a                        of value by a close company</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a173416">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Alteration of share capital</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The participators of a close company are deemed to make a chargeable lifetime gift\u000d\u000a                        where:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is an alteration in, or extinguishment of, the company''s unquoted shares or\u000d\u000a                                loan capital.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>There is an alteration in, or extinguishment of, rights attaching to any shares\u000d\u000a                                in, or\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">debentures</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                of, that company which are unquoted.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Either of the above result in a reduction in the value of the participator''s\u000d\u000a                                estate.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 100 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>However, usual IHT principles apply, so there is no gift where the alteration is done for\u000d\u000a                        genuine commercial purposes and there is no gratuitous intent.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>As with gifts made by close companies, these are not PETs. The comments made\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">above</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        about exemptions therefore apply equally here.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers:\u000d\u000a                        alteration in the share capital of a close company</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a148485">\u000d\u000a                <title>Excluded property</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Certain types of property are excluded from IHT. In some cases the domicile status of the\u000d\u000a                    owner is not relevant and in other cases only non-UK domiciled individuals can benefit from the\u000d\u000a                    exemption.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a231157">\u000d\u000a                    <title>All individuals, regardless of domicile status</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">all</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        individuals (regardless of domicile), the following are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>A future interest in a trust (called a\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">reversionary interest</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                ), provided that:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>it was not purchased; and</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>neither the settlor (nor his spouse or civil partner) owns (or has ever\u000d\u000a                                        owned) the reversionary interest.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 48 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Decorations awarded for bravery (not purchased) (previously Extra Statutory\u000d\u000a                                Concession F19, now\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">section 6(1B)</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                of IHTA 1984). (See\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">Legal update, Order made enacting extra-statutory\u000d\u000a                                    concessions\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                and<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC updates guidance on settlor-trustee\u000d\u000a                                    tax adjustments and awards for gallantry</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>An interest in an "excluded property" trust (unless it is an\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">interest in possession</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                purchased by a UK domiciled individual). Broadly, an excluded property trust is:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>a trust created by a settlor who was neither domiciled nor deemed\u000d\u000a                                        domiciled in the UK when he gave assets to it; and\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>which holds only non-UK assets.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                            <para>For information on the interaction between excluded property trusts and the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                rules, see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC confirms that excluded property\u000d\u000a                                    trumps reservation of benefit for non-dom trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a210614">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals not domiciled in the UK</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals who are\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        domiciled in the UK under general law (whether or not they are "deemed" domiciled for IHT\u000d\u000a                        purposes), exempt UK government securities are also excluded property.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a803400">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals domiciled in the Channel Islands or Isle of Man</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals domiciled in the Channel Islands or the Isle of Man (whether or not they\u000d\u000a                        are "deemed" domiciled for IHT purposes), the following additional assets are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">War savings certificates</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                .\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Premium bonds.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="bold">National Savings and Investment</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                bank deposits.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a198610">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Individuals neither domiciled nor deemed domiciled in the UK</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For individuals who are neither domiciled nor deemed domiciled in the UK, the following\u000d\u000a                        additional assets are excluded:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any non-UK property.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Holdings in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">authorised unit trusts</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                and shares in\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">open ended investment companies</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                (OEICs).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 6 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Property excluded from\u000d\u000a                        Inheritance Tax</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a347385">\u000d\u000a                <title>Exemptions available for both lifetime gifts and on death</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Gifts to certain favoured individuals or bodies are exempt from IHT (and do not use up the nil\u000d\u000a                    rate band). They are as follows:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to a<emphasis role="italic">spouse or civil partner</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">charities</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">political parties</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts of<emphasis role="italic">land to housing associations</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts for<emphasis role="italic">national purposes</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to<emphasis role="italic">heritage maintenance funds</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Transfers to employee trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a78580">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to a spouse or civil partner</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>IHT is not payable on any gift made between spouses or civil partners during lifetime or\u000d\u000a                        on death, provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Both parties are domiciled in the UK for IHT purposes (that is, they are either\u000d\u000a                                domiciled or deemed domiciled in the UK); or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Both parties are domiciled outside the UK for IHT purposes (that is, they are\u000d\u000a                                neither domiciled, nor deemed domiciled in the UK).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 18 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If one spouse or civil partner is domiciled in the UK for IHT purposes and the other is\u000d\u000a                        not, there is an upper limit to the spouse exemption in relation to gifts made to the non-UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse. The limit is \u00a355,000 overall, whether the gifts are made in lifetime or on\u000d\u000a                        death. This limit also applies when calculating the transferable nil rate band that can be\u000d\u000a                        claimed by the personal representatives of a non-UK domiciled spouse who is predeceased by a\u000d\u000a                        UK domiciled spouse.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The spouse exemption is available in full in relation to gifts made to the UK domiciled\u000d\u000a                        spouse.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A useful way to remember this is to consider the rationale. When assets pass from a UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse to a non-UK domiciled spouse, they are potentially leaving the IHT "net"\u000d\u000a                        forever (because the non-UK domiciled spouse may not be subject to IHT on his or her death).\u000d\u000a                        By limiting the spouse exemption in these circumstances, the lion''s share of IHT is secured\u000d\u000a                        on the first spouse''s death.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The government announced in its 2012 Budget on 21 March 2012 that it would publish a\u000d\u000a                        consultation document, with draft legislation, on its plans to increase the amount that a UK\u000d\u000a                        domiciled spouse or civil partner can give to his non-domiciled spouse or civil partner free\u000d\u000a                        from IHT. The legislation will form part of Finance Bill 2013. The consultation will propose\u000d\u000a                        an increase in the spouse exemption from \u00a355,000 to \u00a3325,000 that will then track any future\u000d\u000a                        increases in the nil rate band. There will also be an option for the non-domiciled spouse to\u000d\u000a                        elect to be treated as deemed domiciled so that they can benefit from the unlimited spouse\u000d\u000a                        exemption that gifts to UK-domiciled spouses and civil partners currently enjoy. It is now\u000d\u000a                        known that the consultation will be published in May 2012.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The government published draft legislation on 11 December 2012 to increase the amount that\u000d\u000a                        a UK domiciled individual can transfer to his non-UK domiciled spouse or civil partner free\u000d\u000a                        from IHT. The measure will raise the \u00a355,000 limit to the level of the prevailing IHT nil\u000d\u000a                        rate band. Non-UK domiciled individuals who have a UK domiciled spouse or civil partner will\u000d\u000a                        be able to elect to be treated as UK domiciled for IHT purposes. The legislation will have\u000d\u000a                        effect for transfers made on or after 6 April 2013.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information on the spouse exemption generally, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT\u000d\u000a                        Manual: Spouse or civil partner exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a71944">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to charities</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Outright gifts to UK, EU and Norwegian and Icelandic charities (or to charitable trusts\u000d\u000a                        from which only these charities may benefit) are exempt from IHT (<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            paragraph 1, Schedule 6, Finance Act 2010</emphasis>). For more information on the\u000d\u000a                        definition of charity for tax purposes see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, What is a\u000d\u000a                            charity: definition of charity for tax legislation</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information on the charity exemption for IHT, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT\u000d\u000a                        Manual: Charity exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on the reduced rate of IHT for estates of deceased individuals who leave\u000d\u000a                        10% or more of their net estate to charity, see<emphasis role="italic">The rate of\u000d\u000a                            tax</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a771967">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to political parties</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts to UK political parties are exempt, provided that the party is of sufficient\u000d\u000a                        stature. The requirements are that either of the following applied (as at the last general\u000d\u000a                        election):\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At least two members of the party were elected to the House of Commons.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At least one member of the party was so elected and at least 150,000 votes were\u000d\u000a                                given to candidates who were members of that party.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 24 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts to political\u000d\u000a                        parties</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a551704">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts of land to housing associations</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts of land to housing associations or to registered social landlords are exempt from\u000d\u000a                        IHT (<emphasis role="italic">section 24A , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts to registered housing\u000d\u000a                        associations</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a946913">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts for national purposes</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Gifts for national purposes are exempt from IHT. The IHT legislation contains a list of\u000d\u000a                        bodies and institutions that are covered by this exemption. For example:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The National Gallery or British Museum or another national institution which\u000d\u000a                                exists wholly or mainly for the purpose of preserving a collection of scientific,\u000d\u000a                                historic or artistic interest for the public benefit.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any museum or art gallery in the UK which exists wholly or mainly for the purpose\u000d\u000a                                stated above.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any library, the main function of which is to serve the needs of teaching and\u000d\u000a                                research at a university in the UK.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 25 and Schedule 3 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts for National\u000d\u000a                        Purposes</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In the 2011 Budget, the government announced that it would consult on a proposal to\u000d\u000a                        introduce a tax reduction for taxpayers who give a work of art or historical object of\u000d\u000a                        national importance to the State. The consultation ran from 29 June 2011 to 21 September\u000d\u000a                        2011. On 6 December 2011, the government published draft legislation for inclusion in the\u000d\u000a                        Finance Bill 2012. For further information on this measure and to follow its progress\u000d\u000a                        towards implementation, see<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker\u000d\u000a                            2011-12: Tax reduction for gifts of art to the nation</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a761286">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts to heritage maintenance funds</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Heritage maintenance funds are trusts that maintain historic buildings or land of scenic,\u000d\u000a                        scientific or historic interest. A gift to a heritage maintenance fund is exempt from IHT.\u000d\u000a                        The fund does not incur any ongoing IHT charges as long as it meets the following\u000d\u000a                        conditions:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The trustees must:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>be approved by the Treasury;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>contain at least one trustee from a requisite professional body; and\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>must be resident in the UK when HMRC give their direction as to whether\u000d\u000a                                        the trust qualifies.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The fund must be used (for a minimum period of six years from the date it was\u000d\u000a                                given to the trust) for:\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>the maintenance, repair or preservation of the heritage property;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>other charities that exist for such purposes;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>making provision for public access to the heritage property; or</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>national purposes (see<emphasis role="italic">Gifts for national\u000d\u000a                                        purposes</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 27 and Schedule 4 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>HMRC determines whether the building or land is sufficiently important to merit the\u000d\u000a                        exemption (see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax: conditional exemption\u000d\u000a                            for heritage property: What constitutes heritage property?</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Exemptions: maintenance funds (paragraph IHTM11250)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Capital Taxation and the National Heritage (September 2011)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (Chapter 8).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a583748">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Transfers to employee trusts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A transfer of shares by an individual to an\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">employee benefit trust</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (EBT) is exempt provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The shares are held:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>on trust for the benefit of all or most of the employees or office holders\u000d\u000a                                        of the company; or\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>under an approved profit sharing scheme or share incentive plan.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>At the time of (or within one year of) the transfer, the trustees hold more than\u000d\u000a                                half of the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                    <emphasis role="italic">ordinary shares</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                in the company and have voting control on all questions affecting the company as a\u000d\u000a                                whole.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The trust cannot be used to benefit any shareholder who is entitled to:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>5% or more of any class of shares in the company; or</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>5% or more of its assets on winding up.</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 28 , IHTA 1984.</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Employee Benefit Trusts (from\u000d\u000a                        IHTM42900)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on the IHT issues that arise where an EBT is established by a close\u000d\u000a                        company, see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, HMRC publishes guidance on taxation of\u000d\u000a                            EBTs</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For information on EBTs generally, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Trusts in\u000d\u000a                        commercial transactions: Employee benefit trusts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a563285">\u000d\u000a                <title>Exemptions available for lifetime gifts only</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>Additional exemptions are also available for lifetime gifts, if none of the above exemptions\u000d\u000a                    apply. The most commonly used exemptions are as follows:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Normal expenditure out of income</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Small gifts to any one person</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Wedding and civil partnership gifts</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Annual exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Note that the "normal expenditure out of income" exemption is applied first and the "annual"\u000d\u000a                    exemption is applied last, after all the other exemptions.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a86671">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Normal expenditure out of income</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts are exempt if they form part of the donor''s normal expenditure out of\u000d\u000a                        (after tax) income, provided that the donor is left with sufficient income to maintain his\u000d\u000a                        usual standard of living (<emphasis role="italic">section 21 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>A regular pattern of giving is required, for example meeting annual school fees for a\u000d\u000a                        grandchild or paying the premiums on a life policy for another''s benefit.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The first gift in a series can qualify, provided further gifts are intended. If the donor\u000d\u000a                        dies before making the second gift, there must be sufficient evidence that he intended to\u000d\u000a                        make a series of gifts.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Normal expenditure out of\u000d\u000a                        income</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a516515">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Small gifts to any one person</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts of up to \u00a3250 to any one individual during a tax year are exempt (<emphasis\u000d\u000a                            role="italic">section 20 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). The exemption is only available if the\u000d\u000a                        gift (or gifts) to that individual does not exceed \u00a3250 in total. It is not possible to\u000d\u000a                        carry forward any unused portion to the next tax year.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, an individual makes a number of gifts to the same individual during a tax\u000d\u000a                        year and the gifts total \u00a3300. The small gifts exemption does not apply to any part of the\u000d\u000a                        gift(s).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Specific lifetime exemptions:\u000d\u000a                        small gifts exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a758140">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Wedding and civil partnership gifts</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts on the occasion of a marriage or registration of a civil partnership are\u000d\u000a                        exempt up to certain limits (<emphasis role="italic">section 22 , IHTA 1984</emphasis>). The\u000d\u000a                        amount of the limit depends on the relationship of the donor to the couple, as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Each parent can give \u00a35,000.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Each grandparent (or remoter ancestor) can give \u00a32,500.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Either of the couple can give to each other \u00a32,500.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any other person can give \u00a31,000.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gifts can be made to either party of the marriage or civil partnership, or to the\u000d\u000a                        couple jointly. The gifts can be outright, or in trust (provided that only the couple, their\u000d\u000a                        issue and certain other close family members can benefit).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The gift must take place on or before the ceremony and must be conditional on the ceremony\u000d\u000a                        taking place. The exemption is not available if the ceremony does not take place.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Gifts made in consideration of marriage or registration\u000d\u000a                            of civil partnership .\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a676734">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Annual exemption</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Lifetime gifts (which do not fall into any other exemption) are exempt up to \u00a33,000 a\u000d\u000a                        year. If the annual exemption is (wholly or partly) unused for a particular tax year, the\u000d\u000a                        unused portion may be carried forward for one tax year only. (<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                            Section 19 , IHTA 1984.</emphasis>)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Annual exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a1033263">\u000d\u000a                <title>Potentially exempt transfers</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>A potentially exempt transfer (PET) can be made by an individual. If there are no other\u000d\u000a                    exemptions available, the PET might eventually fall out of charge. PETs are:\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Outright gifts to individuals.</para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Gifts to\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">disabled person''s interests</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            .\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para>When an\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">immediate post-death interest</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            comes to an end and the continuing trust qualifies as a\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">trust for bereaved minors</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            .\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a740822">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Amount of tax charged depends on how long the donor survives</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>PETs are called "potentially" exempt, because if the donor survives for seven years from\u000d\u000a                        the date of the gift, the gift becomes fully exempt.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If the donor fails to survive for seven years, the gift becomes chargeable and will use up\u000d\u000a                        all or part of the donor''s nil rate band. However, the longer the donor survives after\u000d\u000a                        making the gift (subject to surviving at least three years), the lower the IHT. This relief\u000d\u000a                        is called "taper relief" and will be calculated as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <table frame="all">\u000d\u000a                            <tgroup cols="2">\u000d\u000a                                <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="50%"/>\u000d\u000a                                <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="50%"/>\u000d\u000a                                <tbody>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                                <emphasis role="bold">Period between the date of gift and the death\u000d\u000a                                                    of the donor\u000d\u000a                                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                            </para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>\u000d\u000a                                                <emphasis role="bold">Rate of taper relief (applied to the amount of\u000d\u000a                                                    IHT)\u000d\u000a                                                </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                                            </para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>0-3 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>0%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>3-4 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>20%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>4-5 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>40%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>5-6 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>60%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>6-7 years</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>80%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                    <row>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>7 years and over</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                        <entry>\u000d\u000a                                            <para>100%</para>\u000d\u000a                                        </entry>\u000d\u000a                                    </row>\u000d\u000a                                </tbody>\u000d\u000a                            </tgroup>\u000d\u000a                        </table>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Section 7(4) , IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The taper relief is applied to the IHT due,\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        the value of the gift. As result, the full value of the gift (calculated as the "loss to the\u000d\u000a                        donor") uses up all or part of the nil rate band.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Zeb makes a gift of \u00a3400,000 to his son Charlie on 1 April 1998. He made no\u000d\u000a                        other gifts during his lifetime. Zeb dies on 5 March 2002. Because Zeb has failed to survive\u000d\u000a                        for at least seven years from the date of the gift (and as the gift exceeds Zeb''s nil rate\u000d\u000a                        band), IHT will be payable on the gift, calculated as follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para xml:space="preserve">Value of the gift (strictly, the loss to Zeb''s estate): \u00a3400,000.\u000d\u000aLess two annual exemptions (see <emphasis role="italic">  Annual exemption  </emphasis>): \u00a36,000.\u000d\u000aLess the nil rate band on 5 March 2002 (see <emphasis role="italic">  The nil rate band  </emphasis>): \u00a3242,000.\u000d\u000aChargeable value of the gift: \u00a3152,000.</para><para xml:space="preserve">IHT @ 40%: \u00a360,800.\u000d\u000aLess taper relief at 20%: \u00a312,160.\u000d\u000aIHT due on the gift: \u00a348,640.</para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Lifetime transfers: what is a potentially exempt\u000d\u000a                            transfer?\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a981403">\u000d\u000a                <title>10% reduction in rate of inheritance tax for gifts to charity</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>The Finance Act Bill 2012 (F A B 2012) introduce d s a lower death rate of IHT for testators\u000d\u000a                    who leave 10% or more of their net estates to charity (clause 207 and Schedule 32, FB 2012) .\u000d\u000a                    The lower rate of IHT is will be 36%, instead of 40%. The lower rate applies will apply in\u000d\u000a                    relation to the estates of testators who die on or after 6 April 2012 (paragraph 10, Schedule\u000d\u000a                    32, FB 2012) . This will be before FB 2012 receives Royal Assent (probably in July 2012). For\u000d\u000a                    more information on the 10% reduction in IHT, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note,\u000d\u000a                        Inheritance tax: leaving 10% of an estate to charity</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a819637">\u000d\u000a                <title>Relief from inheritance tax</title>\u000d\u000a                <para>If the gift is of a certain type of asset, relief may apply to reduce the amount of IHT\u000d\u000a                    payable, sometimes to nil.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <para>The following reliefs apply automatically:</para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Agricultural property relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>Claims for the following reliefs must be specifically made within two years of the death (or\u000d\u000a                    lifetime gift):\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">Woodlands relief</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    <listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <para><emphasis role="italic">National heritage property - conditional exemption</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </listitem>\u000d\u000a                </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                <para>The reliefs are available both for lifetime gifts and on death,\u000d\u000a                    <emphasis role="bold">except</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                    for woodlands relief, which is only available on<emphasis role="bold">death</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                </para>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a317615">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Business property relief (BPR)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where the conditions are met:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>100% relief is available for:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>unquoted share-holdings;</para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>interests in a business (whether owned as a sole trade or in\u000d\u000a                                        partnership).\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>50% relief is available for:</para>\u000d\u000a                            <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>shares in a quoted company (where the donor had control of the company);\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                                <listitem>\u000d\u000a                                    <para>assets, such as land and buildings, used by the donor''s partnership or\u000d\u000a                                        company.\u000d\u000a                                    </para>\u000d\u000a                                </listitem>\u000d\u000a                            </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter I , Part V, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Generally, the donor must have owned the shares or the business for at least two years\u000d\u000a                        prior to the gift or death. Further, certain types of activities and investments are\u000d\u000a                        excluded from relief. For example, relief is not available if the business or company''s\u000d\u000a                        activities consist mainly in dealing in securities, stocks or shares, land or buildings, or\u000d\u000a                        making or holding investments.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC''s guidance on business property relief, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual:\u000d\u000a                        Business relief and businesses (from paragraph IHTM25000)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a89262">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Agricultural property relief (APR)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where the conditions are met, agricultural property may benefit from relief at 100% or 50%\u000d\u000a                        (depending on who farms the land and how long the land has been owned). Relief is given on\u000d\u000a                        the agricultural value of the land. (<emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part V, IHTA\u000d\u000a                            1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        may also be available (after agricultural property relief has been given), for example,\u000d\u000a                        where a farmer owns the land and farms it as a business.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For further information, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax agricultural property relief:\u000d\u000a                            overview\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Agricultural relief (from paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM24000)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a620983">\u000d\u000a                    <title>National heritage property - conditional exemption</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Where property and assets are important to the UK''s national heritage, IHT can be\u000d\u000a                        deferred, provided that:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>A claim is made within two years of the gift or death.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The recipient of the asset gives an undertaking to allow public access and to\u000d\u000a                                preserve it.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter II , Part II, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The relief is available for both lifetime gifts and on death, although if a lifetime gift,\u000d\u000a                        the property must have been:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Owned by the donor (or his spouse or civil partner) throughout the six-year period\u000d\u000a                                before the gift; or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Inherited (at any time, even within the six-year period before the gift) and a\u000d\u000a                                conditional exemption applied when inherited.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>An IHT charge arises if the undertakings are broken or the recipient disposes of the\u000d\u000a                        property. If the recipient keeps to the undertakings, heritage property can pass down from\u000d\u000a                        generation to generation without any charge to IHT.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For more information, see<emphasis role="italic">Practice note, Inheritance tax:\u000d\u000a                        conditional exemption for heritage property</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC guidance, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Heritage property (from\u000d\u000a                        paragraph IHTM04111)</emphasis>,\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Exemptions - conditional exemption (paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM11260)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Capital Taxation and the National Heritage (September 2011)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (Chapters 4 - 7).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a788464">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Woodlands relief (on death)</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodland may qualify for:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para><emphasis role="italic">Agricultural property relief</emphasis>, if it is\u000d\u000a                                ancillary to farmland.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para><emphasis role="italic">Business property relief</emphasis>, if it is commercial\u000d\u000a                                woodland.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>If neither of these reliefs apply, woodlands relief might be available.</para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodlands relief is only available on death and operates as an IHT deferral. Where the\u000d\u000a                        conditions are met, an election can be made to exclude the value of the timber (but not the\u000d\u000a                        land) from the value of the estate for IHT. When the timber is sold (or given away), the\u000d\u000a                        sale proceeds (or the market value at the date of the gift) is charged to IHT. The election\u000d\u000a                        must be made within two years of death.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Woodlands relief is available where:</para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The deceased owned an interest in the land on which the timber has been growing\u000d\u000a                                (either outright or through a qualifying interest in possession) for at least five\u000d\u000a                                years; or\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The deceased received the interest in the land by gift or inheritance at any time\u000d\u000a                                (including within the five years before death).\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>(<emphasis role="italic">Chapter III , Part V, IHTA 1984</emphasis>.)\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Care needs to be taken before making an election for woodlands relief, because IHT will be\u000d\u000a                        payable on the future sale proceeds (or the market value of the timber, if given away). If\u000d\u000a                        the timber is not worth very much on death (for example, because the trees are still very\u000d\u000a                        young) it would be better\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">not</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        to make the election and to pay the IHT instead.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For HMRC guidance, see<emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: Woodlands (from paragraph\u000d\u000a                        IHTM04371)</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <section3 id="a993114">\u000d\u000a                        <title>EU law</title>\u000d\u000a                        <para>Following the European Court of Justice (ECJ) case\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Theodor J\u00e4ger v Finanzamt Kusel-Landstuhl (Case C-256/06,\u000d\u000a                                European Court reports 2008)\u000d\u000a                            </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            and the European Commission''s formal request to the UK to change its legislation in\u000d\u000a                            relation to APR and woodlands relief (see<emphasis role="italic">Legal update, European\u000d\u000a                                Commission asks UK to amend inheritance tax legislation</emphasis>), the\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">Finance Act 2009</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                            extended the scope of APR and woodlands relief to property within the European Economic\u000d\u000a                            Area. See<emphasis role="italic">Private client tax legislation tracker 2008-09:\u000d\u000a                                Agricultural property relief and woodlands</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                        </para>\u000d\u000a                    </section3>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a            <section1 id="a414325">\u000d\u000a                <title>Anti-avoidance measures</title>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a825995">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Gifts with reservation of benefit</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In order for a lifetime gift to be fully effective for IHT purposes, the donor must give\u000d\u000a                        the property away without any strings attached. If the donor retains a significant benefit\u000d\u000a                        or enjoyment in the property given away, it will remain part of his or her estate for the\u000d\u000a                        purposes of calculating IHT. These gifts are called\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">gifts with reservation of benefit</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (GROBs).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For example, Judy gives her home to her three adult children who live elsewhere. She\u000d\u000a                        transfers the legal title into their joint names.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Judy continues to live at the property rent-free, this is a GROB and the\u000d\u000a                                property remains in her estate for IHT purposes.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>If Judy releases her reservation (for example, by moving out or by paying her\u000d\u000a                                children full market rent), this will be a deemed<emphasis role="italic">\u000d\u000a                                    PET</emphasis>. Provided Judy survives for seven complete years after releasing\u000d\u000a                                the reservation of benefit, the deemed PET will be exempt from IHT.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The rule is that the property must be enjoyed to the "virtual exclusion" of the donor. As\u000d\u000a                        a result, there is some scope for a very minor reservation of benefit. Examples are set out\u000d\u000a                        in\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">IHT manual: The reservation: exclusion of the donor (paragraph\u000d\u000a                            IHTM14333)\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and include the following scenarios:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The donor pays social visits or stays temporarily at a house given away.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>The donor is given the occasional lift in a car given away.</para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>These anti-avoidance provisions are found in\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">section 102</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        of the<emphasis role="italic">Finance Act 1986</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>In addition, there is no GROB where the gift is exempt from IHT, for example gifts to a\u000d\u000a                        spouse or civil partner (see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Exemptions available for both lifetime gifts and on death</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Exemptions available for lifetime gifts only</emphasis>).\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a                <section2 id="a158451">\u000d\u000a                    <title>Pre-owned assets</title>\u000d\u000a                    <para>The GROB provisions were intended to prevent artificial avoidance of IHT by exploiting\u000d\u000a                        loopholes in the legislation. They have not been totally successful, as many schemes\u000d\u000a                        (usually involving houses or chattels) were created to get round the provisions (one example\u000d\u000a                        is the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">home loan scheme</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        ). To combat this, the\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="bold">\u000d\u000a                            <emphasis role="italic">pre-owned assets charge</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        (POAC) was introduced with effect from 6 April 2005.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>Broadly, POAC applies where an individual gives away property (for example land and\u000d\u000a                        buildings, chattels or money and investments) and subsequently benefits from that property\u000d\u000a                        (or property derived from it). If caught, an annual income tax charge is imposed on the\u000d\u000a                        donor in relation to the benefit he receives from the property, unless he elects for the\u000d\u000a                        gift to be taxed as a GROB. The election must be made by the 31 January following the tax\u000d\u000a                        year in which the individual first becomes liable to POAC. (\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">Section 84 and Schedule 15 , Finance Act 2004</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        and<emphasis role="italic">Chapter 8 , Part 5, Income Tax (Trading and Other Income) Act\u000d\u000a                            2005</emphasis>.) For HMRC''s guidance on this matter, including late elections, see\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: IHT manual: Pre-owned assets: Election into inheritance tax\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">see</emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        .\u000d\u000a                        <emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Income tax and pre-owned assets: detailed guidance: Section 3\u000d\u000a                            - The election into Inheritance Tax\u000d\u000a                        </emphasis>\u000d\u000a                        .\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <para>There are a number of exclusions and exemptions; however the broad principles are as\u000d\u000a                        follows:\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                    <itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Property which is subject to IHT in the hands of the donor (for example, property\u000d\u000a                                in which he has reserved a benefit) should not be subject to POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Property which is not subject to IHT because it qualifies for favoured IHT\u000d\u000a                                treatment (for example, because it benefits from an exemption or relief, such as the\u000d\u000a                                <emphasis role="italic">spouse exemption</emphasis>), should not be subject to POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                        <listitem>\u000d\u000a                            <para>Any other property which has been given away, and from which the donor derives a\u000d\u000a                                benefit, should be caught by POAC.\u000d\u000a                            </para>\u000d\u000a                        </listitem>\u000d\u000a                    </itemizedlist>\u000d\u000a                    <para>For full details of HMRC''s guidance on POAC, see<emphasis role="italic">HMRC: Income tax\u000d\u000a                        and pre-owned assets: detailed guidance</emphasis>.\u000d\u000a                    </para>\u000d\u000a                </section2>\u000d\u000a            </section1>\u000d\u000a        </fulltext>\u000d\u000a    </practicenote>\u000d\u000a</xml>\u000d\u000a','2013-03-15 00:00:00.000000','another test')
INSERT INTO PERSON VALUES(1,0,'Valerie Singleton')
